WEBVTT

00:05.639 --> 00:06.807
JUDY WOODRUFF: Good
evening. I'm Judy Woodruff.

00:06.807 --> 00:08.208
GWEN IFILL: And I'm Gwen Ifill.

00:08.208 --> 00:10.043
JUDY WOODRUFF: On the
"NewsHour" tonight:

00:10.043 --> 00:12.312
JOSEPH BIDEN, Vice President of
the United States: While I will
not be a candidate, I

00:12.312 --> 00:14.915
will not be silent.

00:14.915 --> 00:19.620
JUDY WOODRUFF: Vice President
Joe Biden ends months of
speculation -- what his decision

00:19.620 --> 00:23.190
not to run means in the
race for the White House.

00:23.190 --> 00:27.094
GWEN IFILL: Paul Ryan says he is
willing to run for speaker of
the House, but on his own

00:27.094 --> 00:29.296
terms.

00:29.296 --> 00:34.668
JUDY WOODRUFF: Also ahead this
Wednesday: The push to reduce
the nation's prison population

00:34.668 --> 00:40.240
gains unexpected allies. Police
and prosecutors call for fewer
arrests.

00:40.240 --> 00:45.445
GWEN IFILL: And a pioneering
project to uncover the genetic
roots of autism.

00:45.445 --> 00:50.050
LISA WILSON, Mother of Jonathan
Wilson: I called Blair at work,
and I immediately burst

00:50.050 --> 00:54.588
into tears, and I said, this
changes everything and nothing.

00:54.588 --> 00:57.190
GWEN IFILL: All that and more
on tonight's "PBS NewsHour."

00:57.190 --> 01:03.463
(BREAK)

01:03.463 --> 01:16.176
GWEN IFILL: For Democrats, a
season of uncertainty is at an
end: Vice President Joe Biden
will

01:16.176 --> 01:19.579
not join the presidential
race after all.

01:19.579 --> 01:23.817
He'd pondered the possibility at
least since summer, and
announced his decision today in

01:23.817 --> 01:28.455
the White House Rose Garden.
Joined by his wife, Jill, and
President Obama, he said he

01:28.455 --> 01:32.893
and his family took the time to
consider all political options
after his son Beau died

01:32.893 --> 01:35.529
of cancer in may.

01:35.529 --> 01:38.999
JOSEPH BIDEN, Vice President of
the United States:
Unfortunately, I believe we are
out

01:38.999 --> 01:45.439
of time, the time necessary to
mount a winning campaign for the
nomination.

01:45.439 --> 01:52.479
But while I will not be a
candidate, I will not be silent.
This party, our nation will

01:52.479 --> 02:00.988
be making a tragic mistake if we
walk away or attempt to undo the
Obama legacy. The American

02:00.988 --> 02:08.428
people have worked too hard and
we have come too far for that.
Democrats shouldn't only

02:08.428 --> 02:14.901
defend this record and protect
this record. They should run on
this record.

02:14.901 --> 02:20.073
GWEN IFILL: The vice president
urged his party to oppose the
influence of unlimited campaign

02:20.073 --> 02:24.811
contributions and to support
making college more accessible.
He also warned against a

02:24.811 --> 02:28.815
partisan divide that he said
is ripping the country apart.

02:28.815 --> 02:35.655
JOSEPH BIDEN: It's
mean-spirited, it's petty, and
it's gone on for much too long.
I don't

02:35.655 --> 02:40.794
believe, like some do, that it's
naive to talk to Republicans.

02:40.794 --> 02:46.099
I don't think we should look at
Republicans as our enemies. They
are our opposition. They're

02:46.099 --> 02:51.438
not our enemies. And for the
sake of the country, we have to
work together.

02:51.438 --> 02:56.476
GWEN IFILL: The Biden decision
removed a potential challenge to
Democratic front-runner Hillary

02:56.476 --> 03:00.414
Clinton. She, in turn, praised
him as a good friend and a great
man. We will look more

03:00.414 --> 03:04.551
deeply into the decision, and
its implications, after the news
summary.

03:04.551 --> 03:09.222
JUDY WOODRUFF: In other news,
Syria's President Bashar
al-Assad has made a surprise
visit

03:09.222 --> 03:15.829
to Moscow, his first known trip
abroad since civil war broke out
in his country in 2011.

03:15.829 --> 03:21.468
Russia and Syrian officials now
say that Assad held talks
yesterday with Russian President

03:21.468 --> 03:26.440
Vladimir Putin, and that he
expressed gratitude for Russian
support, including from
warplanes

03:26.440 --> 03:29.543
and military helicopters.

03:29.543 --> 03:34.915
BASHAR AL-ASSAD, President of
Syria (through translator): To
begin with, thank you to the

03:34.915 --> 03:39.152
country of Russia. Terrorism
which we see spreading today
could have been more widespread

03:39.152 --> 03:43.757
and more harmful if not for your
decisions and steps. With all
certainty, a political

03:43.757 --> 03:48.061
solution decided upon by the
people of Syria is the future of
Syria in the way that we

03:48.061 --> 03:51.465
envision, and this
is everyone's goal.

03:51.465 --> 03:57.437
JUDY WOODRUFF: News of the visit
wasn't confirmed until Assad was
safely back in Damascus. Also

03:57.437 --> 04:02.142
today, the Russians announced
that Foreign Minister Sergei
Lavrov will meet with Secretary

04:02.142 --> 04:06.079
of State John Kerry on Friday in
Vienna. They will be joined by
counterparts from Saudi

04:06.079 --> 04:08.715
Arabia and Turkey.

04:08.715 --> 04:14.087
GWEN IFILL: Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu drew
a storm of criticism today

04:14.087 --> 04:18.458
for linking the Holocaust to a
Palestinian leader from World
War II.

04:18.458 --> 04:23.363
In Jerusalem yesterday,
Netanyahu cited a 1941 meeting
involving the grand mufti of

04:23.363 --> 04:26.233
Jerusalem, a known
Nazi sympathizer.

04:26.233 --> 04:32.772
BENJAMIN NETANYAHU, Israeli
Prime Minister: He had a central
role in fomenting the final

04:32.772 --> 04:38.278
solution. He flew to Berlin.
Hitler didn't want to
exterminate the Jews at the
time.

04:38.278 --> 04:42.415
He wanted to expel the Jews. And
Haj Amin al-Husseini went there
and said, "If you expel

04:42.415 --> 04:44.551
them, they will all come here."

04:44.551 --> 04:47.721
"So, what should I do
with them?" he asked.

04:47.721 --> 04:50.490
He said, "Burn them."

04:50.490 --> 04:55.128
GWEN IFILL: Palestinians, along
with Holocaust experts and
survivors and the chancellor of

04:55.128 --> 04:59.366
Germany, said the comment was
factually wrong, and could
incite violence.

04:59.366 --> 05:03.170
Today, as Netanyahu left on a
trip to Germany, he said he's
not absolving Hitler, but he

05:03.170 --> 05:07.440
argued it's absurd to ignore
the mufti's statements.

05:07.440 --> 05:12.812
JUDY WOODRUFF: President Obama
called today for better
physician training and other
steps

05:12.812 --> 05:18.418
to battle an epidemic of
prescription drug abuse and
heroin use. He traveled to
Charleston

05:18.418 --> 05:23.223
in West Virginia, the state with
the highest rate of overdose
deaths in the country. There,

05:23.223 --> 05:26.860
he said he will press for
expanded treatment for addicts.

05:26.860 --> 05:32.866
GWEN IFILL: Toyota has ordered a
new recall, this time for a
faulty power window switch

05:32.866 --> 05:37.604
that can overheat and
potentially cause a fire. The
automaker says more than
six-and-a-half

05:37.604 --> 05:42.576
million vehicles worldwide are
affected. Some two million of
those are in the U.S.

05:42.576 --> 05:47.314
Toyota was hit by fines in the
U.S. after a 2009 scandal over
faulty floor mats, brakes

05:47.314 --> 05:49.816
and gas pedals.

05:49.816 --> 05:54.621
JUDY WOODRUFF: And Wall Street
had another down day, after
another batch of disappointing

05:54.621 --> 06:01.728
corporate earnings. The Dow
Jones industrial average lost 48
points to close at 17168.

06:01.728 --> 06:07.867
The Nasdaq fell almost 41
points, and the S&P 500 slid
nearly 12.

06:07.867 --> 06:13.506
Still to come on the "NewsHour":
Joe Biden, what does it mean
that he's not running?;

06:13.506 --> 06:18.945
Paul Ryan says he will serve as
House speaker, but only if;
colder weather brings more
trouble

06:18.945 --> 06:28.121
for thousands of
migrants, and much more.

06:28.121 --> 06:38.565
GWEN IFILL: It has been a
months-long waiting game, but
now that we know Vice President

06:38.565 --> 06:41.768
Biden will not make another run
for the White House, what drove
his decision, and what does

06:41.768 --> 06:45.872
it mean for the rest
of the 2016 field?

06:45.872 --> 06:49.643
Glenn Thrush, the chief
political correspondent for
Politico, has been covering
this, and

06:49.643 --> 06:53.113
in many ways was able to see
around the corner in this
magazine profile earlier this
year,

06:53.113 --> 06:54.748
"Joe Biden in Winter."

06:54.748 --> 06:57.350
Glenn joins me now.

06:57.350 --> 07:00.754
So, after all the ups and the
downs and the speculation, no
go. Why?

07:00.754 --> 07:05.425
GLENN THRUSH, Politico: No, I
mean, there is a number of
reasons, sort of bifurcated

07:05.425 --> 07:09.562
between his emotional life and
this terrible tragedy that he
suffered with the death of

07:09.562 --> 07:14.801
his 46-year-old son, Beau, in
May, but also there was really
no political path.

07:14.801 --> 07:19.973
Biden is sort of a political
procrastinator. He's a very
improvisational politician and

07:19.973 --> 07:24.477
he really waited too long.
Hillary Clinton's performance in
the first debate and this
commensurate

07:24.477 --> 07:28.048
rise in the polls that she saw
afterwards simply left him with
no path.

07:28.048 --> 07:32.018
GWEN IFILL: Your story that you
posted this afternoon, you quote
someone as saying that

07:32.018 --> 07:35.855
all the meetings, all the
speculation, all the ways they
were running traps was more

07:35.855 --> 07:38.892
fantasy football than football.

07:38.892 --> 07:43.396
GLENN THRUSH: Yes, I think he
was really confined to a
relatively small group of
advisers. Shouldn't

07:43.396 --> 07:46.900
surprise folks who know the way
that Biden operates, a lot of
his family.

07:46.900 --> 07:52.472
His son Hunter, his remaining
son, was really pushing him for
this. Also, Mike Donilon,

07:52.472 --> 07:56.743
a longtime aide from Delaware,
was pushing this. But the rest
of the family was fairly

07:56.743 --> 08:01.781
ambivalent and his larger circle
of advisers were more
facilitating what he wanted to
do,

08:01.781 --> 08:04.117
but I think many of them over
time came to believe that he
ultimately wouldn't go for

08:04.117 --> 08:05.785
it.

08:05.785 --> 08:09.589
GWEN IFILL: Another thing that
you wrote in your earlier piece,
it talked about one of

08:09.589 --> 08:13.259
his friends and advisers saying
that in his career Joe Biden had
climbed almost all the

08:13.259 --> 08:15.995
way to the top, and then
someone moved the ladder.

08:15.995 --> 08:16.996
GLENN THRUSH: Can you imagine
what that must feel like?

08:16.996 --> 08:18.498
GWEN IFILL: Yes.

08:18.498 --> 08:22.635
GLENN THRUSH: This is a guy who
has done everything -- quote,
unquote -- "right."

08:22.635 --> 08:29.142
The problem is, at some point,
he reached, I think, his own
ceiling. The 1988 presidential

08:29.142 --> 08:32.045
campaign, which was disastrous
for him, he was accused of
plagiarizing Neil Kinnock's

08:32.045 --> 08:33.113
speeches, a U.K. politician.

08:33.113 --> 08:35.749
GWEN IFILL: Yes.

08:35.749 --> 08:41.488
GLENN THRUSH: Really, I think
that was his moment. In 2008, he
ran a very bad presidential

08:41.488 --> 08:47.861
campaign. I think Biden is
really an example of, when a
politician has a moment and they

08:47.861 --> 08:53.333
cannot capitalize on that
moment, the rest of their career
really is a postscript.

08:53.333 --> 08:57.003
GWEN IFILL: What was the
significance of doing this in
the Rose Garden with not only
his

08:57.003 --> 08:59.139
wife, but President
Obama by his side?

08:59.139 --> 09:01.808
GLENN THRUSH: Well, the initial
significance for those of us who
were still wondering what

09:01.808 --> 09:03.643
was happening, we knew then he
was going to say no. He wasn't
going to say yes standing

09:03.643 --> 09:06.279
next to the president.

09:06.279 --> 09:10.884
But I think the significance is
that Joe Biden views himself as
both a family man, as symbolized

09:10.884 --> 09:14.921
by his wife -- getting Jill on
board was one of the big
challenges for this. And he
never

09:14.921 --> 09:18.758
really quite closed the
deal with his own wife.

09:18.758 --> 09:23.730
But the more important point
here is, he views himself very
much as a partner with President

09:23.730 --> 09:27.400
Obama, and that relationship,
which really had its ups an
downs in the first term, has

09:27.400 --> 09:29.903
really deepened into something
more personal. I have been
told...

09:29.903 --> 09:32.672
GWEN IFILL: He went out of his
way today to embrace that
legacy.

09:32.672 --> 09:34.908
GLENN THRUSH: Yes. And
apparently after this, they
embraced in the Oval Office. It
was sort

09:34.908 --> 09:37.877
of a tearful moment.

09:37.877 --> 09:44.117
And the president, I am told,
has been very, very concerned
about Biden's state of mind

09:44.117 --> 09:47.487
subsequent to Beau Biden's
death. This is something that
really weighs on everyone.

09:47.487 --> 09:50.123
GWEN IFILL: So he said today
the window had closed.

09:50.123 --> 09:52.425
Was it Hillary Clinton basically
who closed the window?

09:52.425 --> 09:57.630
GLENN THRUSH: I think she sort
of slammed it on his fingers.

09:57.630 --> 10:02.135
If Hillary Clinton had performed
badly in that first debate or
there had been more damaging

10:02.135 --> 10:04.871
revelations about the e-mails
that had come out, I think we
might be dealing with a
different

10:04.871 --> 10:08.541
fact set. But my sense
is that really did it.

10:08.541 --> 10:10.877
GWEN IFILL: And she went out of
her way, we can take a look, to
be very gracious in her

10:10.877 --> 10:13.780
response to him.

10:13.780 --> 10:17.116
She said, among other things:
"Joe Biden is a good man and a
great vice president. I'm

10:17.116 --> 10:21.087
confident that history isn't
finished with Joe Biden. As he
said today, there is more

10:21.087 --> 10:24.657
work to do, and if I know Joe,
he will always be on the front
lines, always fighting for

10:24.657 --> 10:27.527
all of us."

10:27.527 --> 10:30.763
Now, let's just talk polls. With
Joe Biden out of the race,
Hillary Clinton can afford

10:30.763 --> 10:32.499
to be as gracious as she is.

10:32.499 --> 10:34.734
GLENN THRUSH: Oh, absolutely.

10:34.734 --> 10:39.038
I think it is a good day. I'm
sure she had a nice cup of tea
and watched this thing several

10:39.038 --> 10:44.878
times. Look, in all of the polls
that we have seen, Biden takes
away from Hillary Clinton's

10:44.878 --> 10:49.682
support in battleground states
and nationally as well. So what
this means is that I think

10:49.682 --> 10:51.651
it's quite likely we are going
to see a bump in the national
polls and in New Hampshire

10:51.651 --> 10:55.154
and in Iowa for Hillary Clinton.

10:55.154 --> 10:58.291
GWEN IFILL: No Bernie Sanders
bump out of this? None of the
people who are supporting

10:58.291 --> 11:01.394
Bernie Sanders were
drawing toward Biden?

11:01.394 --> 11:06.933
GLENN THRUSH: Yes, Biden is a
fairly centrist -- you could
make the argument Joe Biden,

11:06.933 --> 11:08.535
in the longer span of his
career, has actually been more
conservative than Hillary
Clinton

11:08.535 --> 11:10.370
on a lot of things.

11:10.370 --> 11:14.407
He has tacked to the left, as
everyone in the Democratic Party
has recently, but Biden's

11:14.407 --> 11:20.380
affiliation is with the white
working-class voters. And Bernie
Sanders much more appeals

11:20.380 --> 11:23.883
to the sort of coastal elites. I
think Sanders will see a little
bit of a bump, because I'm

11:23.883 --> 11:26.986
sure some supporters will flock
to him. But I think Hillary
Clinton is the one who is

11:26.986 --> 11:29.322
going to be the
predominant recipient.

11:29.322 --> 11:31.958
GWEN IFILL: And, finally, the
vice president seemed to signal
today this is not the end

11:31.958 --> 11:34.961
of his career. He still
wants to be heard.

11:34.961 --> 11:38.398
Is there any history of a
second-term vice president who
is not running for president

11:38.398 --> 11:41.034
being heard after
finally withdrawing?

11:41.034 --> 11:42.902
GLENN THRUSH: I think you make a
very good point here. I think
his moment of maximum

11:42.902 --> 11:45.672
leverage has passed.

11:45.672 --> 11:50.043
I think the one thing that is
left is an endorsement. As we
know -- and I covered Hillary
Clinton

11:50.043 --> 11:54.714
in 2007 and 2008 -- there are a
lot of bumps left in this road,
and she will need to pull

11:54.714 --> 11:58.084
some endorsements out of her
pocket during times of need. I
think the final card that

11:58.084 --> 12:00.486
he has to play is
an endorsement.

12:00.486 --> 12:02.589
GWEN IFILL: Well, we will be all
waiting for that, that it will
have a huge impact, perhaps,

12:02.589 --> 12:05.124
perhaps not.

12:05.124 --> 12:11.864
That's the thing we like about
campaigns, Glenn Thrush of
Politico. Thank you very much.

12:11.864 --> 12:18.438
GLENN THRUSH: Great being here.

12:18.438 --> 12:24.210
JUDY WOODRUFF: From a decision
made to another one pending.

12:24.210 --> 12:29.282
Wisconsin Congressman Paul Ryan
has told his fellow Republicans
that he is willing to serve

12:29.282 --> 12:33.119
as speaker of the House of
Representatives, but only if
divided groups of conservatives

12:33.119 --> 12:36.255
endorse him first.

12:36.255 --> 12:41.127
Political director Lisa
Desjardins reports on a busy day
in the search for a leader.

12:41.127 --> 12:44.597
LISA DESJARDINS: The could-be
speaker laid out his demands
Tuesday night: unified party

12:44.597 --> 12:47.467
backing and family time.

12:47.467 --> 12:51.504
REP. PAUL RYAN (R), Wisconsin: I
have shown my colleagues what I
think success looks like,

12:51.504 --> 12:55.942
what I think it takes to unify
and leads and how my family
commitments comes first. I have

12:55.942 --> 12:59.212
left this decision
in their hands.

12:59.212 --> 13:05.318
LISA DESJARDINS: Paul Ryan's
clear ultimatum landed in a
packed, wild Capitol this
morning.

13:05.318 --> 13:08.655
Reporters surrounded lawmakers
in the conservative House
Freedom Caucus, the rebellious
group

13:08.655 --> 13:12.592
that Ryan says must
sign on for him to run.

13:12.592 --> 13:16.229
But members like Alabama's Mo
Brooks were cool to the idea.

13:16.229 --> 13:20.500
REP. MO BROOKS (R), Alabama: I
don't think there is any
question that a significant
number

13:20.500 --> 13:27.340
of members of the Republican
Conference have coerced,
cajoled, induced Paul Ryan to
run

13:27.340 --> 13:30.076
for speaker of the House when
he doesn't want that job.

13:30.076 --> 13:34.080
LISA DESJARDINS: Idaho's Raul
Labrador is another Freedom
Caucus member.

13:34.080 --> 13:33.479
REP. RAUL LABRADOR (R), Idaho:
There's a lot of people who can
do it. Jason Chaffetz would

13:33.479 --> 13:36.516
be a very good speaker
of the House.

13:36.516 --> 13:41.621
LISA DESJARDINS: While many
members avoided questions and
sought out the elevators,
current

13:41.621 --> 13:45.124
Speaker John Boehner pushed
for stability and Ryan.

13:45.124 --> 13:48.361
REP. JOHN BOEHNER (R-OH),
Speaker of the House: Listen, I
think Paul is going to get the
support

13:48.361 --> 13:54.567
that he is looking for. I
thought he laid out a very clear
vision for how he would run

13:54.567 --> 13:57.937
the speakership. And I thought
the members responded very well
to it.

13:57.937 --> 14:01.441
LISA DESJARDINS: Moderate Peter
King of New York was less sure
that Ryan would get enough

14:01.441 --> 14:04.010
support, and therefore
more worried.

14:04.010 --> 14:05.378
REP. PETER KING (R), New York: I
don't see who else it could be.
If it's not Paul Ryan,

14:05.378 --> 14:07.980
then I think it's a disaster.

14:07.980 --> 14:11.484
LISA DESJARDINS: Already, some
outside conservatives are on the
attack. A group called the Tea

14:11.484 --> 14:17.590
Party Patriots released a video
highlighting Ryan's support of
the 2008 stimulus bill.

14:17.590 --> 14:20.893
REP. PAUL RYAN: This bill
offends my principles, but I'm
going to vote for this bill in
order

14:20.893 --> 14:23.996
to preserve my principles.

14:23.996 --> 14:29.035
LISA DESJARDINS: That underlines
the divide for Republicans, who
face a Friday deadline

14:29.035 --> 14:33.272
set by Ryan. The Wisconsin
representative is using his
leverage to see if he can take

14:33.272 --> 14:37.043
command without becoming
a political casualty.

14:37.043 --> 14:41.447
REP. PAUL RYAN: What I told
members is, if you can agree to
these requests, and if I

14:41.447 --> 14:47.120
can truly be a unifying figure,
then I will gladly serve.

14:47.120 --> 14:51.491
JUDY WOODRUFF: And Lisa
joins us from the Capitol.

14:51.491 --> 14:55.862
So, Lisa, this doesn't sound
like a done deal. It's nightfall
there. What are you hearing?

14:55.862 --> 14:57.997
LISA DESJARDINS: That's right.

14:57.997 --> 15:02.168
The members of the House Freedom
Caucus just got out of a meeting
with Paul Ryan. Congressman

15:02.168 --> 15:05.671
Ryan had very little to say, but
he told our Quinn Bowman, our
producer here, the meeting

15:05.671 --> 15:09.075
went well. He said it was a
nice meeting. But that's it.

15:09.075 --> 15:13.312
We did get more information from
the Freedom Caucus members, and
I think you put it the

15:13.312 --> 15:18.184
best way there, that this is
still up in the air, Judy. They
are going to meet again later

15:18.184 --> 15:21.754
tonight. They may vote tonight
and that vote may be the most
significant part of this fight

15:21.754 --> 15:24.924
this week. The vote could
be tomorrow as well.

15:24.924 --> 15:29.095
But the reason that vote is very
difficult for Mr. Ryan is that
the House of Freedom

15:29.095 --> 15:33.399
Caucus has their own internal
rules, Judy, where they will
only support a candidate if

15:33.399 --> 15:38.905
80 percent of their members
agree to do so. You are talking
then about 80 percent of the

15:38.905 --> 15:43.176
most conservative members of the
House of Representatives, the
members who wanted John

15:43.176 --> 15:46.579
Boehner out and some of whom are
pretty openly saying they are
not so sure about Paul Ryan

15:46.579 --> 15:48.614
either.

15:48.614 --> 15:54.020
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, we know the
rest of the Republican
membership in the House of
Representatives

15:54.020 --> 15:59.859
supports Paul Ryan, but how
influential is anybody in the
outside with these Freedom

15:59.859 --> 16:04.397
Caucus members? I mean, who do
they listen to? Who can
influence them?

16:04.397 --> 16:09.202
LISA DESJARDINS: I think these
are members who listen most of
all to their core constituency.

16:09.202 --> 16:13.139
But that does include not just
the voters in their districts,
who do skew very conservative.,

16:13.139 --> 16:16.075
that is why they have been
elected, but who also -- they
also listen to, say,
conservative

16:16.075 --> 16:19.412
talk radio and the Tea Party.

16:19.412 --> 16:23.816
As we put in the package, some
Tea Party groups have already
come out against Paul Ryan
today.

16:23.816 --> 16:28.721
And that's something that is a
factor in these members'
decisions the next couple of
days.

16:28.721 --> 16:32.625
JUDY WOODRUFF: Lisa, you were
telling me just a few minutes
ago that there is now some
discussion

16:32.625 --> 16:37.597
about trying to deal with
raising the debt ceiling before
there's a vote on a new speaker.

16:37.597 --> 16:40.166
What about that?

16:40.166 --> 16:43.536
LISA DESJARDINS: This is a very
tricky game of chess happening
right now. Not only is

16:43.536 --> 16:46.405
the House trying to bring in a
new leader, but they're also
trying to manage three different

16:46.405 --> 16:50.009
crises coming soon.

16:50.009 --> 16:55.214
And speaking to a top Republican
aide in leadership currently
told me tonight that they would

16:55.214 --> 17:01.220
like to pass an increase in the
debt ceiling before there is a
new speaker, before next

17:01.220 --> 17:06.525
week's vote, which may include
Mr. Ryan. And that vote, Judy,
on the debt ceiling could

17:06.525 --> 17:10.596
come as soon as this week. It's
something that those in power
now in the House want

17:10.596 --> 17:14.767
to do before any new
speaker comes into power.

17:14.767 --> 17:17.436
JUDY WOODRUFF: But we also know
it's something the members of
the Freedom Caucus, most
conservative

17:17.436 --> 17:18.738
members, presumably,
wouldn't want.

17:18.738 --> 17:21.607
LISA DESJARDINS:
Yes, that's right.

17:21.607 --> 17:25.411
And here is where you get into
the complexity of this
situation. The House Freedom
Caucus

17:25.411 --> 17:31.284
realizes that they don't have
potentially another viable
candidate outside of Paul Ryan,

17:31.284 --> 17:35.454
but at the same time, they're
trying to get, I think, as much
out of the situation as they

17:35.454 --> 17:40.660
can, trying to get as many
guarantees as they can from him
about their own agenda.

17:40.660 --> 17:46.599
And that includes trying to get
as many concessions from
Democrats on the debt ceiling.
So it's

17:46.599 --> 17:50.836
complicated. The debt ceiling
might be a factor here in their
discussions with Mr. Ryan, but,

17:50.836 --> 17:54.307
moreover, they're questioning
whether they think he will
actually change things in the

17:54.307 --> 17:58.778
House. One congressman, Raul
Labrador, said to me and other
reporters, you know, we all

17:58.778 --> 18:02.448
like Paul Ryan, but this isn't
about personality. We're just
not sure he can change things
because

18:02.448 --> 18:05.518
he hasn't changed things
yet in the House.

18:05.518 --> 18:09.889
You follow that line of
thinking, if you are outside of
that conservative caucus, Judy,

18:09.889 --> 18:13.559
and it still doesn't make it
clear what the endgame is. I
think tonight could be an
important

18:13.559 --> 18:17.163
night. We will see what the
Freedom Caucus does. And, of
course, Friday is the deadline

18:17.163 --> 18:22.068
that Mr. Ryan set as to whether
he will be viable to run for
speaker.

18:22.068 --> 18:26.939
JUDY WOODRUFF: Lisa Desjardins
watching it all very closely at
the Capitol, thank you.

18:26.939 --> 18:36.482
LISA DESJARDINS: Thank you.

18:36.482 --> 18:44.256
GWEN IFILL: As winter approaches
across Europe, migrants and
refugees desperate to enter the

18:44.256 --> 18:47.360
E.U. face even
bigger challenges.

18:47.360 --> 18:51.163
Hari Sreenivasan
reports from Greece.

18:51.163 --> 18:56.502
HARI SREENIVASAN: Billowing
smoke signified the latest
threat to the thousands crossing

18:56.502 --> 19:01.607
Southern Europe: fire. It
erupted at a camp along
Slovenia's border with Croatia
and jumped

19:01.607 --> 19:05.444
from tent to tent, likely
sparked by bonfires, as migrants
struggled to keep warm. There

19:05.444 --> 19:08.881
was no word of casualties.

19:08.881 --> 19:13.686
The camp is one of many that
Slovenia has filled to capacity
since thousands began arriving

19:13.686 --> 19:19.325
from Croatia over the weekend. A
number of people in the camp had
just arrived after

19:19.325 --> 19:25.231
a brutal 24 hours. During the
night, a train from Croatia
released them near the frontier.

19:25.231 --> 19:31.737
Then, in near-freezing
temperatures, they were forced
to wade across a river.

19:31.737 --> 19:41.380
MAN: It was very cold. It was a
very big -- after that, we
decided to come in here. We need

19:41.380 --> 19:44.884
help. We need dress.
We need food.

19:44.884 --> 19:49.388
HARI SREENIVASAN: After the
fire, many in the camp were
taken away on buses headed north

19:49.388 --> 19:54.360
to Austria. Elsewhere today,
hundreds waited in fields
guarded by Slovenian authorities

19:54.360 --> 19:57.063
waiting to be told
where to go next.

19:57.063 --> 20:01.467
MAN: I do not think it's Europe
like this, but when I come to
here, so difficult. I'm

20:01.467 --> 20:05.671
sorry for Europe. Europe is sad.

20:05.671 --> 20:09.742
HARI SREENIVASAN: The Slovenes
have appealed to the European
Union for help. And early

20:09.742 --> 20:12.244
today, their Parliament
authorized a greater role for
the army, guarding the border
with

20:12.244 --> 20:15.714
Croatia.

20:15.714 --> 20:19.652
Thousands more migrants have
trekked through Greece and
Macedonia to Serbia, where
they're

20:19.652 --> 20:24.623
pressing to continue their own
journeys into Western Europe.
Overnight, some 3,500 spent

20:24.623 --> 20:29.195
the night in the freezing cold
at the Serbian-Croatian border
after Croatian officials closed
the

20:29.195 --> 20:31.330
gates.

20:31.330 --> 20:38.737
WOMAN: The situation is very
challenging. The people were
here all the night. They spend

20:38.737 --> 20:45.211
all the night, because the
border was temporarily closed,
that such a capacity was very
slow.

20:45.211 --> 20:50.983
So, many families with children,
elderly people, people with
disability were spending the
night

20:50.983 --> 20:52.952
here.

20:52.952 --> 20:57.890
HARI SREENIVASAN: Scuffles broke
out as the frustration of
waiting proved too much for

20:57.890 --> 21:02.328
some. As before, others took
matters into their own hands,
crossing fields and orchards

21:02.328 --> 21:05.898
at dawn, evading police
where they could.

21:05.898 --> 21:09.468
Meanwhile, in Vienna, the head
of Croatia's police met with his
counterparts from Hungary,

21:09.468 --> 21:12.004
Slovenia and Austria.

21:12.004 --> 21:16.675
VLADO DOMINIC, Croatian Police
Director (through translator):
The daily influx from Macedonia

21:16.675 --> 21:21.247
and Serbia into Croatia is about
10,000 migrants. They are
transferred every day towards
the

21:21.247 --> 21:25.851
Slovenian border, and Slovenia
moves them towards Austria. We
must stem the migrant

21:25.851 --> 21:29.822
crisis as soon as possible, so
that we reduce the number of
migrants arriving to Europe.

21:29.822 --> 21:33.526
HARI SREENIVASAN: To that end,
the president of the European
Commission called a Sunday

21:33.526 --> 21:39.632
summit of the Balkan states and
others. But the human surge
showed no signs of abating.

21:39.632 --> 21:44.003
In Greece, three giant ferries a
day are bring refugees to
Athens' main port from the Greek

21:44.003 --> 21:46.705
islands where they land.

21:46.705 --> 21:51.710
This ship, which arrived just
before dawn, carried roughly
2,000 people, most of them

21:51.710 --> 21:56.182
headed on to buses to take them
north. By now, though, some like
Mohammad Ghunaim, a

21:56.182 --> 21:59.118
Syrian medical student, have
tempered their enthusiasm.

21:59.118 --> 22:02.555
MOHAMMAD GHUNAIM, Syrian Medical
Student: Very happy and excited,
but I have to make

22:02.555 --> 22:08.961
my own plan. I have to make my
own future right now. Europe is
not a big dream. You

22:08.961 --> 22:12.097
will make your dream. It's like
the American dream. How -- the
American dream, you will

22:12.097 --> 22:14.333
make your dream.

22:14.333 --> 22:17.736
HARI SREENIVASAN: Many more were
following that dream across the
Aegean Sea from Turkey

22:17.736 --> 22:20.839
today, despite the
mounting hardships.

22:20.839 --> 22:27.112
More than 500 people survived
heavy rains and thundershowers
to get to the island of

22:27.112 --> 22:31.951
Lesbos on their flimsy boats
today. When they got there,
there wasn't enough shelter.
Volunteers

22:31.951 --> 22:36.522
had already run out of rain
covers, leaving children
standing in the rain. These
migrants

22:36.522 --> 22:40.593
and refugees understand that the
weather will certainly get
worse.

22:40.593 --> 22:44.196
They're also starting to get
concerned about the climate, the
uncertain climate toward

22:44.196 --> 22:47.166
migrants across much
of the European Union.

22:47.166 --> 22:52.905
In Athens, for the "PBS
NewsHour," Hari Sreenivasan.

22:52.905 --> 23:02.715
JUDY WOODRUFF: Stay with us.

23:02.715 --> 23:08.687
Coming up on the "NewsHour":
what to know before Hillary
Clinton testifies on Benghazi;

23:08.687 --> 23:16.028
the search for clues to the
causes of autism; and finding
inspiration in the natural
world.

23:16.028 --> 23:19.965
But first to the latest in
our Broken Justice series.

23:19.965 --> 23:24.536
We have done a number of stories
about calls for reform from
voices across the spectrum.

23:24.536 --> 23:29.608
Tonight, we hear a new call from
top law enforcement officials
themselves.

23:29.608 --> 23:36.282
Today, more than 130 of them,
including police chiefs and
prosecutors, came to Washington

23:36.282 --> 23:42.154
to push for changes to
incarceration and policing
practices. One of the key
reforms they want

23:42.154 --> 23:48.027
to see, reducing or eliminating
prison time for nonviolent
offenses and some drug
possession

23:48.027 --> 23:50.763
charges.

23:50.763 --> 23:55.834
Garry McCarthy is the
superintendent of the Chicago
Police Department. He's co-chair
of

23:55.834 --> 24:01.073
this coalition. And Benjamin
David is the district attorney
for New Hanover and Pender

24:01.073 --> 24:03.942
Counties in Eastern
North Carolina.

24:03.942 --> 24:05.811
And welcome to both of you.

24:05.811 --> 24:06.712
GARRY MCCARTHY, Chicago Police
Superintendent: Thanks for
having us.

24:06.712 --> 24:09.515
JUDY WOODRUFF: So,
Superintendent McCarthy, let me
start with you.

24:09.515 --> 24:13.686
You said today -- among other
things, you said, we incarcerate
the wrong people. We

24:13.686 --> 24:16.355
measure the wrong things when it
comes to the criminal justice
system. What are you

24:16.355 --> 24:18.490
referring to?

24:18.490 --> 24:23.896
GARRY MCCARTHY: I'm referring to
the fact that the violent
offenders, repeat offenders

24:23.896 --> 24:29.968
are too frequently on our
streets causing problems. About
two months ago, I came down

24:29.968 --> 24:34.740
to D.C. again with about 30
different jurisdictions across
the country that all have
increases

24:34.740 --> 24:37.676
in violent crime this year.

24:37.676 --> 24:42.214
And the one commonality that we
had, repeat offenders over and
over again. So, there are

24:42.214 --> 24:46.819
some people who, I'm sorry, do
not deserve to be out in our
society. They're dangerous.

24:46.819 --> 24:49.621
There are other people that
can actually be reformed.

24:49.621 --> 24:54.893
And what we find over and over
again is the low-level narcotics
offender is sometimes

24:54.893 --> 24:59.965
incarcerated at a greater rate
than the violent criminal. In
Cook County -- in Chicago, which

24:59.965 --> 25:06.905
is in Cook County, 28 percent of
the inmates who are incarcerated
in Cook County Jail are

25:06.905 --> 25:12.811
there for narcotics-related
offenses, yet less than 4
percent are there for gun
possession.

25:12.811 --> 25:15.481
And these are folks with violent
criminal histories. That's
causing a danger in our

25:15.481 --> 25:17.516
streets.

25:17.516 --> 25:23.155
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, District
Attorney David, what is an
example of an offense that -- we

25:23.155 --> 25:27.793
just heard it has to do with
narcotics, for example. So, if
somebody is carrying around

25:27.793 --> 25:31.397
a small amount of heroin or
cocaine, they shouldn't be
arrested? What should happen

25:31.397 --> 25:33.132
to them?

25:33.132 --> 25:33.132
BENJAMIN DAVID, District
Attorney, New Hanover and Pender
Counties, North Carolina: No,
they

25:33.132 --> 25:37.836
should be arrested, but to be
clear, justice reinvestment in
North Carolina, where I serve

25:37.836 --> 25:42.775
as the district attorney, we
make it mandatory that they are
going to receive probation for

25:42.775 --> 25:47.212
a drug possession case, and to
have the opportunity for a
deferred prosecution.

25:47.212 --> 25:52.017
We went one step further and
also made it where you could
expunge the nonviolent criminal

25:52.017 --> 25:55.954
history of a felon or someone
with a misdemeanor for that
one-time offense, so that they
could

25:55.954 --> 26:00.859
stay eligible for things like
public housing, student loans,
military service, and they

26:00.859 --> 26:03.128
don't have that scarlet letter
on them when they are trying to
get a job, because that

26:03.128 --> 26:05.864
is really what we
are talking about.

26:05.864 --> 26:10.869
The second that we put them into
the system, they're on a
different statistical path.

26:10.869 --> 26:15.107
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, are you
saying, in effect,
Superintendent McCarthy, that
somebody who

26:15.107 --> 26:19.812
is out there who has -- say they
have an open container of
alcohol or, as you know, we
mentioned

26:19.812 --> 26:24.450
carrying around drugs, you are
assuming that that is not on the
pathway to committing more

26:24.450 --> 26:26.051
violent offenses?

26:26.051 --> 26:29.221
GARRY MCCARTHY: Well, you know,
I'm not going to make that leap.

26:29.221 --> 26:34.993
But what I can tell you is that
there are people who have
violent criminal histories

26:34.993 --> 26:41.900
that need to be incarcerated.
And those individuals who don't
may not be -- may not need to be

26:41.900 --> 26:45.938
incarcerated. Different
prosecution, different method of
dealing with it. It doesn't mean

26:45.938 --> 26:48.006
we're not going to
make the arrest.

26:48.006 --> 26:52.277
But what happens once that
arrest is made, when that
individual goes into the system?

26:52.277 --> 26:57.249
Can they get deferred from
prosecution into drug treatment
programs or something along

26:57.249 --> 27:01.987
those lines? There is a
difference between carrying a
gun, an illegal gun, and getting

27:01.987 --> 27:06.225
caught with some heroin, a
total difference there.

27:06.225 --> 27:10.762
JUDY WOODRUFF: I understand
that. But I still want to just
clarify this. So, are you
saying,

27:10.762 --> 27:17.436
both of you saying, District
Attorney David, that, for
example, that all those years of

27:17.436 --> 27:25.377
arguing just say no, that drugs
-- stay away from drugs, that
they are a pathway to getting

27:25.377 --> 27:29.214
addicted to heroin, that all
those messages were the wrong
messages?

27:29.214 --> 27:32.484
BENJAMIN DAVID: No, I don't say
that at all. I still say stay
away from drugs. It brings

27:32.484 --> 27:35.187
the wolf to the door. It feeds
all the violence in our
communities right now. It's the
very

27:35.187 --> 27:38.156
gasoline for the
engine of crime.

27:38.156 --> 27:43.896
What we are really saying is
that we need to have the right
people in custody. And mentally

27:43.896 --> 27:48.534
ill drug addicts are not who we
want to clog up the prisons and
the jails with. It is a

27:48.534 --> 27:51.036
scarce resource when are you
talking about those beds. And we
want to put the career

27:51.036 --> 27:54.506
and violent criminals
in those places.

27:54.506 --> 27:57.776
JUDY WOODRUFF: But this is going
to be an expensive, more
expensive approach, isn't

27:57.776 --> 28:01.647
it, Superintendent McCarthy? You
are going to require people with
experience in handling

28:01.647 --> 28:05.484
people with drug addiction,
giving people therapy.

28:05.484 --> 28:08.253
GARRY MCCARTHY: Right.

28:08.253 --> 28:12.090
JUDY WOODRUFF: You're going to
require -- it's going to require
more people, more man-hours,

28:12.090 --> 28:14.326
woman-hours to deal with this.

28:14.326 --> 28:17.262
GARRY MCCARTHY: I don't believe
so. I don't believe so, because,
if you think about it,

28:17.262 --> 28:24.603
we're not changing the behavior
of the drug-addicted individual
by incarcerating them. We may
change

28:24.603 --> 28:29.107
behavior of the gun carrier by
incarcerating them, because he's
not addicted to the gun

28:29.107 --> 28:31.977
like the heroin user might
be addicted to the heroin.

28:31.977 --> 28:37.649
It is the wrong medicine for
what ails us. If we -- we want
to correct the behavior,

28:37.649 --> 28:42.220
the way you correct the behavior
of a drug user is to get them
drug treatment, not
incarcerating

28:42.220 --> 28:46.725
them. The way that you change
the behavior of a bad guy who
carries a gun, you put them

28:46.725 --> 28:49.561
in jail. This prevents them from
committing another crime while
he is in there and maybe

28:49.561 --> 28:52.097
he won't do it again
when he comes out.

28:52.097 --> 28:56.501
JUDY WOODRUFF: What is involved,
Mr. David, in changing the laws
to make this happen,

28:56.501 --> 28:58.236
what you are describing?

28:58.236 --> 29:01.440
BENJAMIN DAVID: Well, first of
all, it is outreach efforts and
understanding, first

29:01.440 --> 29:04.743
and foremost, who we are really
talking about now, with the
biggest victims of violent crime

29:04.743 --> 29:07.846
are also from the same
high-crime neighborhoods.

29:07.846 --> 29:12.184
And when you have a business
model where 98 percent of the
people we are putting in prison

29:12.184 --> 29:16.822
are getting out, and they're not
getting out better, and 66
percent of them are back in

29:16.822 --> 29:20.892
that prison cell within three
years charged with new offenses,
what we're doing is not

29:20.892 --> 29:24.329
protecting the community
in the way that we can.

29:24.329 --> 29:28.000
And so what we really have to do
is, when you are talking about
funding, we're going

29:28.000 --> 29:31.903
to save money by closing some
prisons and not having to build
other ones. That is the

29:31.903 --> 29:37.809
North Carolina experience. But
we are going to use that money,
reinvest it into drug treatment,

29:37.809 --> 29:41.179
into mental health reform, into
having some of the things that
we can do to divert these

29:41.179 --> 29:44.316
cases out of the
criminal justice system.

29:44.316 --> 29:50.255
It involves not only government,
but the business community,
getting people jobs, and getting

29:50.255 --> 29:55.027
schools to stop the
school-to-prison pipeline we
could talk about. There are so
many people

29:55.027 --> 29:57.462
in a community other than law
enforcement, because this is
bigger than police and
prosecutors

29:57.462 --> 29:59.865
can handle on their own.

29:59.865 --> 30:03.835
JUDY WOODRUFF: And one other
philosophy, I guess, that has
been behind us, Superintendent

30:03.835 --> 30:07.339
McCarthy, and that's the
so-called broken windows
approach, going after people who
have

30:07.339 --> 30:13.211
committed minor offenses because
you are afraid they are going to
do something worse.

30:13.211 --> 30:16.248
Is that saying that whole
approach was the wrong approach?

30:16.248 --> 30:21.286
GARRY MCCARTHY: No, not -- the
same issue. It's not that we're
not going to address those

30:21.286 --> 30:25.390
conditions. As a matter of fact,
broken windows is the number one
complaint at our community

30:25.390 --> 30:29.261
meetings from the people
who live in the community.

30:29.261 --> 30:34.032
They want us to address those
low-level issues. The question
is, how is it that we address

30:34.032 --> 30:39.337
them? If we were putting people
in prison for 20 years for
public consumption of alcohol,

30:39.337 --> 30:42.441
that law would change very
quickly. But what we are doing
is, we are putting people in

30:42.441 --> 30:47.279
prison for extended sentences
for low-level amounts of
narcotics.

30:47.279 --> 30:51.983
And that just doesn't work. You
can issue somebody a ticket for
drinking a beer in public

30:51.983 --> 30:56.354
vs. arresting them. You can also
take that drug user and divert
them into a program,

30:56.354 --> 30:59.157
instead of incarcerating them.

30:59.157 --> 31:03.662
JUDY WOODRUFF: Superintendent
Garry McCarthy from Chicago and
District Attorney Ben David

31:03.662 --> 31:05.063
from North Carolina,
we thank you both.

31:05.063 --> 31:05.964
BENJAMIN DAVID: Thank you.

31:05.964 --> 31:08.066
GARRY MCCARTHY:
Pleasure. Thank you.

31:08.066 --> 31:12.738
JUDY WOODRUFF: We recorded that
interview late this afternoon.
And I also asked Superintendent

31:12.738 --> 31:18.610
McCarthy about recently
published allegations of a
pattern of abuse at a police
detention

31:18.610 --> 31:23.281
center in Chicago. He says those
allegations are false. You can
watch his comments online

31:23.281 --> 31:32.357
on our Web site,
PBS.org/NewsHour.

31:32.357 --> 31:45.237
GWEN IFILL: The 2012 attack on
the U.S. Consulate and CIA
