sparked

31:45.237 --> 31:50.675
a firestorm of recrimination and
accusation, touching on policy
and politics.

31:50.675 --> 31:55.180
As former Secretary of State
Hillary Clinton prepares to
testify before a congressional

31:55.180 --> 31:58.483
committee about the attacks
tomorrow, chief foreign affairs
correspondent Margaret Warner

31:58.483 --> 32:02.687
catches us up on the
facts of the case.

32:02.687 --> 32:08.326
MARGARET WARNER: This fiery
scene at the U.S. Consulate in
Benghazi, Libya, took place
three

32:08.326 --> 32:13.565
years ago, but it sparked a
political war of words that's
still being fought.

32:13.565 --> 32:19.304
Thirteen months after the fall
of dictator Moammar Gadhafi,
Benghazi was lawless and

32:19.304 --> 32:26.111
awash with guns. The U.S.
mission was protected by one
local militia and unarmed
contractor

32:26.111 --> 32:31.950
guards. On the anniversary of
9/11, around 9:40 p.m., heavily
armed men stormed the compound,

32:31.950 --> 32:36.121
opening fire and torching
some of its buildings.

32:36.121 --> 32:42.427
Hours later, a CIA annex less
than a mile away came under
mortar attack. U.S. Ambassador

32:42.427 --> 32:47.532
Christopher Stevens died in the
main compound, along with
Foreign Service officer Sean
Smith,

32:47.532 --> 32:52.971
apparently of smoke inhalation.
Two contractors, ex-Navy SEALs
Tyrone Woods and Glen Doherty,

32:52.971 --> 32:56.141
died at the annex.

32:56.141 --> 33:01.746
Then-Defense Secretary Leon
Panetta said U.S. commanders had
no intelligence that an attack

33:01.746 --> 33:06.751
was coming on the Benghazi
mission, and U.S. forces were
too far away to help when it
did.

33:06.751 --> 33:10.622
LEON PANETTA, Former U.S.
Defense Secretary: Frankly,
without an adequate warning,
there

33:10.622 --> 33:17.629
wasn't enough time, given the
speed of the attack, for armed
military assets to respond.

33:17.629 --> 33:21.833
MARGARET WARNER: In the
aftermath, the military did
deploy elite teams of U.S.
Marines from

33:21.833 --> 33:28.673
Rota, Spain, one to Benghazi to
evacuate personnel, the other to
fortify the U.S. Embassy in
Tripoli.

33:28.673 --> 33:34.646
The Benghazi assault followed
anti-U.S. protests that day in a
half-dozen Islamic countries.

33:34.646 --> 33:38.850
In Cairo, a mob breached the
walls of the heavily-fortified
U.S. Embassy, tearing down

33:38.850 --> 33:43.421
the U.S. flag. No
Americans were harmed.

33:43.421 --> 33:49.461
All those protests were against
an American citizen's online
movie mocking the Prophet

33:49.461 --> 33:54.099
Mohammed. Five days later, on
the Sunday talk shows, then-U.N.
Ambassador Susan Rice pointed

33:54.099 --> 33:56.067
to a linkage.

33:56.067 --> 33:58.770
SUSAN RICE, U.S. National
Security Adviser: What this
began as was a spontaneous, not

33:58.770 --> 34:03.441
a premeditated, response to
what had transpired in Cairo.

34:03.441 --> 34:07.312
MARGARET WARNER: But Republicans
charged the White House knew
almost immediately Benghazi

34:07.312 --> 34:13.551
was a terror attack, and
concealed it to protect
President Obama's reelection
campaign.

34:13.551 --> 34:18.023
The administration insisted
Ambassador Rice was speaking
from the best information
available

34:18.023 --> 34:22.694
at the time. Four months later,
then-Secretary of State Hillary
Clinton took on Senate
Republicans

34:22.694 --> 34:24.763
at a hearing.

34:24.763 --> 34:27.465
HILLARY RODHAM CLINTON (D),
Presidential Candidate: The fact
is, we had four dead Americans.
Was

34:27.465 --> 34:31.536
it because of a protest or was
it because of guys out for a
walk one night who decided

34:31.536 --> 34:37.442
they would go kill some
Americans? What difference at
this point does this make? It is
our job

34:37.442 --> 34:42.580
to figure out what happened and
do everything we can to prevent
it from ever happening again.

34:42.580 --> 34:46.985
MARGARET WARNER: The incident
launched parallel investigations
by the FBI, the State
Department,

34:46.985 --> 34:52.490
and Congress to do just that.
One was by an independent
accountability review board
appointed

34:52.490 --> 34:57.729
by Secretary Clinton and headed
by retired former Ambassador
Thomas Pickering.

34:57.729 --> 35:03.268
That December, it issued a
stinging report on what happened
that night. And it called

35:03.268 --> 35:07.639
the consulate's security posture
inadequate for Benghazi and
grossly inadequate to deal

35:07.639 --> 35:09.874
with the attack.

35:09.874 --> 35:13.345
THOMAS PICKERING, Former U.S.
Ambassador to the United
Nations: It was deficient in
security

35:13.345 --> 35:19.050
supplies. It was probably
deficient in the security
manning of the post.

35:19.050 --> 35:25.657
There were ongoing security
problems in Benghazi, which we
felt should have alerted the
department

35:25.657 --> 35:31.229
to deal with those issues. Many
of the questions presented to
the department were answered

35:31.229 --> 35:35.300
in the negative, when they
probably should have been
positively responded to.

35:35.300 --> 35:37.402
MARGARET WARNER: And are you
saying there were requests for
additional security there

35:37.402 --> 35:39.604
and they were denied?

35:39.604 --> 35:42.941
THOMAS PICKERING: There was an
ongoing request for additional
security, and a number of them

35:42.941 --> 35:48.480
were not responded to
properly and positively, yes.

35:48.480 --> 35:53.018
MARGARET WARNER: The Pickering
review cited -- quote --
"systemic failures and
leadership

35:53.018 --> 35:58.857
and management deficiencies at
the State Department, a
consulate that was severely
under-resourced

35:58.857 --> 36:04.562
with regard to certain needed
security equipment, and a
short-term staff rotation that
resulted

36:04.562 --> 36:10.301
in diminished institutional
knowledge, continuity and
mission capacity."

36:10.301 --> 36:13.772
Pickering said the review board
closely examined whether the
U.S. military could have
scrambled

36:13.772 --> 36:17.175
forces elsewhere to
the attack site.

36:17.175 --> 36:22.914
THOMAS PICKERING: And it was
very clear to us that the
nearest assistance was called

36:22.914 --> 36:30.221
upon right away, but the
requirement to mobilize aircraft
and move those Marines in Spain
wasn't

36:30.221 --> 36:32.991
sufficient to get
it there in time.

36:32.991 --> 36:36.327
MARGARET WARNER: Three State
Department officials resigned
immediately after that report.
The

36:36.327 --> 36:39.364
report didn't fault
Secretary Clinton.

36:39.364 --> 36:43.468
Did you try to follow the chain
of command, as it were, the
chain of responsibility all

36:43.468 --> 36:44.602
the way to the top?

36:44.602 --> 36:46.171
THOMAS PICKERING: Absolutely.

36:46.171 --> 36:49.607
MARGARET WARNER: So, did it ever
go to the secretary of state?

36:49.607 --> 36:52.744
THOMAS PICKERING: I had no
indication that any of these
decisions went to the secretary

36:52.744 --> 36:54.846
of state.

36:54.846 --> 36:58.817
MARGARET WARNER: And do these
decisions usually go to the
secretary of state?

36:58.817 --> 37:01.686
THOMAS PICKERING: No, they
wouldn't normally go to the
secretary of state. These were
decisions

37:01.686 --> 37:06.624
about should we provide X-kind
of money to build a wall?

37:06.624 --> 37:11.629
MARGARET WARNER: Meanwhile, the
man charged as a ringleader of
the Benghazi attacks, Ahmed

37:11.629 --> 37:15.366
Abu Khattala, faces a federal
trial in Washington after being
captured by U.S. special forces

37:15.366 --> 37:17.702
last year.

37:17.702 --> 37:25.310
I'm Margaret Warner for the
"PBS NewsHour" in Washington.

37:25.310 --> 37:39.057
JUDY WOODRUFF: One in every 68
children in the U.S. is
diagnosed as being on the autism

37:39.057 --> 37:45.430
spectrum. It's long been known
that genetics plays a role in
the neurodevelopmental disorder.

37:45.430 --> 37:51.936
Now scientists believe they have
the tools to identify which gene
variants trigger autism

37:51.936 --> 37:58.176
and with that information
diagnose and treat it much
earlier. A project called MSSNG
has

37:58.176 --> 38:02.747
brought together an unusual
partnership and is giving hope
to affected families.

38:02.747 --> 38:04.849
Special correspondent
Jackie Judd reports.

38:04.849 --> 38:07.519
WOMAN: What's the
highest you can go?

38:07.519 --> 38:11.890
JACKIE JUDD: In the cloud, he is
known only by eight digits,
attached to a map of his

38:11.890 --> 38:12.490
DNA.

38:12.490 --> 38:15.360
WOMAN: Oh, you can go high.

38:15.360 --> 38:19.531
JACKIE JUDD: On the ground, at
his home outside of Toronto,
Jonathan Wilson is known as a

38:19.531 --> 38:23.234
bright and sometimes
aggressive 14-year old.

38:23.234 --> 38:26.004
LISA WILSON, Mother of Jonathan
Wilson: From day one -- and,
literally, I mean day one

38:26.004 --> 38:29.741
-- he was very different
from my other newborns.

38:29.741 --> 38:33.444
BLAIR WILSON, Father of Jonathan
Wilson: I remember, with the
other children, I would

38:33.444 --> 38:37.849
hold them over my shoulder and
cuddle with them. And John would
just arch his back, wouldn't

38:37.849 --> 38:41.553
want to be -- wouldn't
want to be held.

38:41.553 --> 38:48.059
JACKIE JUDD: It wasn't until
Jonathan was almost 3 that he
was diagnosed with autism.

38:48.059 --> 38:52.497
That was based on what doctors
could observe, his behavior and
the absence of typical
developmental

38:52.497 --> 38:54.365
milestones.

38:54.365 --> 38:59.737
JONATHAN WILSON, Autistic: It's
hard for me to know when to
speak, hard to communicate.

38:59.737 --> 39:01.639
BLAIR WILSON: Watch
where you're shooting.

39:01.639 --> 39:06.911
JACKIE JUDD: But it was only
recently that Lisa and Blair
Wilson learned, with great

39:06.911 --> 39:14.519
precision, why their son is
autistic: a spontaneous genetic
mutation on chromosome 16.

39:14.519 --> 39:21.993
LISA WILSON: I got the phone
call, and it stopped me in my
tracks, and I called Blair

39:21.993 --> 39:29.400
at work, and I immediately burst
into tears, and I said, this
changes everything and nothing.

39:29.400 --> 39:35.907
Nothing changes about how we
live our lives, but he now is
able to say, definitively; I

39:35.907 --> 39:39.677
have autism. I was born
with it. It's genetic.

39:39.677 --> 39:42.914
MAN: These machines actually are
able to sequence millions and
millions of DNA fragments.

39:42.914 --> 39:48.720
JACKIE JUDD: The call came from
researchers here at Toronto's
Hospital for Sick Children,

39:48.720 --> 39:54.158
which is a partner in a
pioneering project to identify
genetic variants responsible for

39:54.158 --> 39:56.861
autism.

39:56.861 --> 40:03.401
Jonathan, his parents and his
three brothers all had their
entire DNA mapped or sequenced,

40:03.401 --> 40:07.505
so researchers could see the
most minute deletions or
duplications.

40:07.505 --> 40:08.906
DR. STEPHEN SCHERER, Toronto
Hospital for Sick Children:
Every time a new genome comes

40:08.906 --> 40:11.776
in, we can run a dynamic
kind of reassessment.

40:11.776 --> 40:15.246
JACKIE JUDD: Dr. Stephen
Scherer, whose team reviewed
Jonathan's genome, is one of the

40:15.246 --> 40:17.882
world's leading geneticists.

40:17.882 --> 40:21.919
DR. STEPHEN SCHERER: Now we have
the capability to do the ideal
experiment, and that is to

40:21.919 --> 40:26.658
sequence the entire genome, the
entire complement of DNA of all
of these families, and decode

40:26.658 --> 40:29.927
the underpinnings of autism.

40:29.927 --> 40:36.434
JACKIE JUDD: And, from that,
diagnose and treat autism
possibly from birth, as well

40:36.434 --> 40:43.241
as identify other health
problems often associated with
the disorder.

40:43.241 --> 40:48.946
Autism Speaks began the MSSNG
project with the audacious goal
of completing the DNA mapping

40:48.946 --> 40:54.085
of 10,000 people affected by
autism and then making that
information widely available in

40:54.085 --> 40:56.921
a single place.

40:56.921 --> 41:00.591
Rob Ring is the advocacy
organization's chief science
officer.

41:00.591 --> 41:04.662
ROB RING, Chief Science Officer,
Autism Speaks: In that database
will be families, individuals

41:04.662 --> 41:11.035
touched by autism, their
siblings, parents, all their
genomes. That is a massive data

41:11.035 --> 41:11.569
set.

41:11.569 --> 41:14.138
JACKIE JUDD: How massive?

41:14.138 --> 41:20.244
ROB RING: It's huge. It's the
equivalent of a -- watching a
high-definition TV show
streaming

41:20.244 --> 41:23.948
continuously for 13.5 years.

41:23.948 --> 41:30.588
JACKIE JUDD: Autism Speaks had
the will and the resources, $50
million, to undertake the

41:30.588 --> 41:36.894
project. The Hospital for Sick
Children had the expertise to
map an individual's DNA,

41:36.894 --> 41:41.999
which now costs only $1,000 and
takes only a couple of weeks to
go from blood sample

41:41.999 --> 41:45.770
to complete gene mapping.

41:45.770 --> 41:52.110
What to do with that massive
amount of data being generated
led them to a third partner

41:52.110 --> 41:59.050
not known for its work in
genetics. It led them to Google.
Most consumers know Google

41:59.050 --> 42:03.721
as the go-to search engine to
sort information about everyday
things, like restaurant rankings

42:03.721 --> 42:07.225
or weather patterns.

42:07.225 --> 42:12.797
For the MSSNG project, Google
stores participants' genomes in
the cloud and then applies its

42:12.797 --> 42:16.701
vast analytic power to
questions from researchers.

42:16.701 --> 42:18.936
DAVID GLAZER, Google Genomics:
To date, this is the biggest.

42:18.936 --> 42:22.807
JACKIE JUDD: David Glazer heads
Google's growing genomics
division.

42:22.807 --> 42:27.678
DAVID GLAZER: What we realized a
couple years ago is that the
world of biology has started

42:27.678 --> 42:32.450
to generate a lot more
information than they
historically had tools to work
with.

42:32.450 --> 42:35.953
And that's what we at Google are
really good at, is taking large
amounts of information

42:35.953 --> 42:40.625
and finding the value in that
information. What we're doing
with the MSSNG project is

42:40.625 --> 42:45.563
saying, you guys are generating
and gathering, from all the
volunteer families, this really

42:45.563 --> 42:50.935
valuable set of information. Let
us help make that information as
valuable as possible.

42:50.935 --> 42:57.642
JACKIE JUDD: So far, 76
researchers from six countries,
exploring the causes of autism,

42:57.642 --> 43:03.147
including environmental factors,
have gained entry to the new
portal. And they are posing

43:03.147 --> 43:07.618
questions that only powerful
search engines could process.

43:07.618 --> 43:12.590
DAVID GLAZER: We had to build
tools that could work with data
sets that were trillions of

43:12.590 --> 43:17.495
rows of information. That's
trillions with a T. That tool is
good at working with lots

43:17.495 --> 43:21.199
and lots of information and
finding patterns in an
interactive way.

43:21.199 --> 43:25.770
DR. STEPHEN SCHERER: Right away,
we get some information that
helps in developing new
diagnostic

43:25.770 --> 43:31.742
tests. And, secondly, we can
think about new medicines. This
is the problem right now.

43:31.742 --> 43:35.680
The challenge is, for the core
features of autism, there's no
effective medical treatment.

43:35.680 --> 43:41.352
JACKIE JUDD: The researchers
applying for entry to the DNA
library in the cloud pay

43:41.352 --> 43:46.924
nothing if approved. That is
unique in a field where access
to data can be closely guarded

43:46.924 --> 43:49.126
and expensive.

43:49.126 --> 43:55.266
ROB RING: Our central thesis, if
you will, around MSSNG was, the
more eyes we can get

43:55.266 --> 44:01.572
on a data set like that, the
greater the probability that
discoveries are going to be
made, discoveries

44:01.572 --> 44:06.611
that have the potential to
transform how we think about
autism, how we diagnose it, and

44:06.611 --> 44:10.147
ultimately how we treat it.

44:10.147 --> 44:15.920
JACKIE JUDD: The optimism of
MSSNG's founders about the
potential for unlimited
discovery

44:15.920 --> 44:20.591
is apparent. And they believe
that what works for autism may
work for any number of other

44:20.591 --> 44:22.360
diseases.

44:22.360 --> 44:26.063
DAVID GLAZER: They will all
build on each other, and the
success of one will help all.

44:26.063 --> 44:30.535
JACKIE JUDD: In fact, Google
already is exploring a project
in the cancer field.

44:30.535 --> 44:34.805
DAVID GLAZER: The model is in
the pattern of how to take this
kind of information and

44:34.805 --> 44:39.977
allow scientists to ask the
kinds of questions they want.
There are thousands of very rare

44:39.977 --> 44:45.750
diseases that would benefit from
having a deeper genomic
understanding of their
condition.

44:45.750 --> 44:52.757
JACKIE JUDD: Lisa and Blair
Wilson hope their contributions
to MSSNG spare other parents

44:52.757 --> 44:56.427
some of the anguish they
experienced when they knew that
something was wrong with their

44:56.427 --> 44:59.497
little boy, just not what.

44:59.497 --> 45:07.738
LISA WILSON: I think starting
intervention at age 3 was very
late, compared to how early

45:07.738 --> 45:14.612
our concerns began about him.
And if we could have intervened
earlier in the trajectory

45:14.612 --> 45:18.316
of his development, we could
have influenced it sooner.

45:18.316 --> 45:23.354
BLAIR WILSON: And I think that
would have really helped him
along his journey.

45:23.354 --> 45:30.094
JACKIE JUDD: So far, MSSNG has
put the genomes of 2,300 people
in the cloud, and all 10,000

45:30.094 --> 45:38.169
are expected to be up by next
spring, among them, the
complicated map of a Canadian
teenager

45:38.169 --> 45:44.308
with the simple hope of one day
living an independent life
filled with family and friends.

45:44.308 --> 45:53.117
For the "PBS NewsHour," this
is Jackie Judd in Toronto.

45:53.117 --> 46:05.196
GWEN IFILL: Whether it is the
vibrant colors of autumn leaves,
or the smell of crisp mountain

46:05.196 --> 46:09.300
air, nature has inspired poets
for centuries, including one of
this year's MacArthur grant

46:09.300 --> 46:11.969
winners.

46:11.969 --> 46:14.872
Ellen Bryant Voigt takes us on a
journey through her poetry and
the countryside that serves

46:14.872 --> 46:17.108
as her muse.

46:17.108 --> 46:22.313
ELLEN BRYANT VOIGT, Poet: My
name is Ellen Bryant Voigt. I'm
a poet and a teacher. I

46:22.313 --> 46:27.218
live in rural Vermont. I
have been here since 1969.

46:27.218 --> 46:33.557
When I look back over all the
poems that I have written, I
notice a couple of concerns

46:33.557 --> 46:41.132
or obsessions that kept
recurring. And one of them has
to do with the relationship
between

46:41.132 --> 46:46.237
the individual soul and the
collective, however you want to
define collective. We might
define

46:46.237 --> 46:53.244
it as family. You can define
that as small town, the world,
the natural world.

46:53.244 --> 47:02.253
And very often, that individual
soul is in conflict with the
larger one. And that, I

47:02.253 --> 47:09.593
think, I can trace back to
coming from lots and lots of
relatives close by in a small

47:09.593 --> 47:12.563
area, a small town that
knew all of your business.

47:12.563 --> 47:14.398
(LAUGHTER)

47:14.398 --> 47:20.905
ELLEN BRYANT VOIGT: "If you have
been, let's say, a
glass-half-empty kind of girl,
you

47:20.905 --> 47:28.846
wake to the chorus of geese
overhead, forlorn, for something
has softened their nasal voices,

47:28.846 --> 47:34.485
their ugly aggression. On the
ground, they're worse than
chickens. But flying, one leader

47:34.485 --> 47:40.458
falling back, another moving up
to pierce the wind. No one in
charge or every one in

47:40.458 --> 47:47.331
charge, in flight, each limited
goose adjusts its part in the
cluster just under the clouds.

47:47.331 --> 47:54.538
Do they mean together to
duplicate the cloud?"

47:54.538 --> 48:00.344
I have a great interest in the
rhythms of the natural world. I
try to observe it. And

48:00.344 --> 48:07.184
then I try to come to some
understanding that I didn't have
before. Poetry allowed me to

48:07.184 --> 48:11.822
observe it, and then to try to
find the language that is
precise enough for the
complexities

48:11.822 --> 48:18.929
around that world.

48:18.929 --> 48:27.905
I think I have always looked for
a high degree of solitude. Music
was a wonderful haven for

48:27.905 --> 48:35.212
me as a child. It was a place
that -- where I could find that
solitude and find something

48:35.212 --> 48:43.888
I was passionate about. Music,
to my mind, is a crucial part of
all poems, the rhythm

48:43.888 --> 48:49.026
of it, the rhythm of the line,
the long vowel, the short vowel.

48:49.026 --> 48:55.633
If I can hear a line that is
intriguing and is interesting
rhythmically, then I can go

48:55.633 --> 49:01.839
follow it toward my 50 to 100
drafts, which is about how long
it takes me to do a poem.

49:01.839 --> 49:04.508
"Storm."

49:04.508 --> 49:12.183
"One minute, a slender pine
indistinguishable from the
others, the next, its trunk
horizontal,

49:12.183 --> 49:20.457
still green, the jagged stump a
nest for the flickers. One
minute, high wind and rain,

49:20.457 --> 49:28.599
the skies lit up, the next, a
few bright winking stars, the
lashing of the brook. One
minute,

49:28.599 --> 49:34.839
an exaltation in the apple
trees, the shadblow trees, the
next, white trash on the ground,

49:34.839 --> 49:39.476
new birds, or the same birds
crowding the feeder."

49:39.476 --> 49:46.684
To write poems, I have to remind
myself sometimes to go out into
the world. I love the natural

49:46.684 --> 49:51.789
beauty. I love living in the
country. I love the solitude.
But to only that, to live on

49:51.789 --> 49:57.361
the mountaintop, I think,
wouldn't be good for poems.

49:57.361 --> 50:05.669
I think that poetry has become
more visible and more a part of
the fabric of the culture

50:05.669 --> 50:11.308
than it's often referred to.
More books of poetry are being
published now than ever before.

50:11.308 --> 50:15.246
I think that there's a
great hunger for that.

50:15.246 --> 50:21.518
It's -- we get a lot of
information. We're bombarded
with information. But I think,
especially

50:21.518 --> 50:27.024
in this country, there are very
few ways in which we can process
any of that or that we

50:27.024 --> 50:31.495
can think hard about that. We
need to slow down in order to
think hard about it. And

50:31.495 --> 50:38.002
the poem will slow us down.
It will slow us down.

50:38.002 --> 50:50.781
JUDY WOODRUFF: Finally,
to our "NewsHour" Shares.

50:50.781 --> 50:56.120
Today's, it one of our online
videos. And it's about the
personal testimonies of drug

50:56.120 --> 51:01.258
addiction and its impact in West
Virginia. As we heard earlier,
President Obama traveled

51:01.258 --> 51:06.597
to that state today, where he
took part in a community forum
on those very problems.

51:06.597 --> 51:11.735
High schoolers from our Student
Reporting Lab in Richwood, West
Virginia, attended the

51:11.735 --> 51:14.171
event. They interviewed members
of the community affected by all
this.

51:14.171 --> 51:16.674
Here's an excerpt.

51:16.674 --> 51:21.578
DARLENE CLUTTER, Librarian: I
have got a sister that died a
few months ago that was just a

51:21.578 --> 51:28.252
few years younger than me
because she became addicted to
medications that the doctors had

51:28.252 --> 51:30.688
prescribed to her.

51:30.688 --> 51:34.725
LAKIN CLARK, Recovering Addict:
I started using drugs when I was
like 12, probably smoking

51:34.725 --> 51:37.628
weed, just -- probably
just to fit in.

51:37.628 --> 51:41.532
AMY PODDEY, Recovering Addict: I
got arrested on two felony
delivery charges.

51:41.532 --> 51:47.071
DENISE HUGHES, Recovering
Addict: I got arrested on two
felony delivery charges, and as
part

51:47.071 --> 51:52.409
of my bond stipulation, I had to
go to DRC. I have been in there
13 months.

51:52.409 --> 51:57.247
LAKIN CLARK: And I just didn't
-- I didn't know how to live
without drugs. It was how

51:57.247 --> 52:00.484
I felt I had to have them to get
up in the morning. I had to have
them to do anything.

52:00.484 --> 52:03.687
I had to have them to live.

52:03.687 --> 52:06.991
AMY PODDEY: When it is
happening, you don't really
realize that the drugs are
taking over

52:06.991 --> 52:09.326
your body and your mind. You
think that everything is still
OK.

52:09.326 --> 52:12.529
DENISE HUGHES: I have tried -- I
mean, I have tried a lot. I have
not done heroin, but have

52:12.529 --> 52:18.502
I done my share. And it's not
something I'm proud of. It's
wrecked my life.

52:18.502 --> 52:24.808
AMY PODDEY: I have two children.
I have a 10-year-old and a
13-year-old. And for those

52:24.808 --> 52:30.214
two years, I didn't wake up
thinking, I got to get my kids
up for school or I got to do

52:30.214 --> 52:33.884
this. I woke up thinking, how
am I going to get high today?

52:33.884 --> 52:40.758
LAKIN CLARK: What I learned
today is addiction is a disease,
and it kills people. It really

52:40.758 --> 52:42.593
does.

52:42.593 --> 52:46.697
AMY PODDEY: My little boy, one
day, we were at GoMart. He said,
"Mom, will you me a chocolate

52:46.697 --> 52:48.632
milk?" And I said, "I don't have
enough money to." But I had 50
bucks in my pocket and I

52:48.632 --> 52:50.667
went and bought a pill with it.

52:50.667 --> 52:54.872
LAKIN CLARK: I never had much to
do with my son. I would take him
to my mom's house and

52:54.872 --> 53:00.744
I would leave him there for days
at a time, sometimes weeks.

53:00.744 --> 53:06.283
DARLENE CLUTTER: So, for me, you
know, it was just -- it is
heart-wrenching, because

53:06.283 --> 53:09.119
I have seen so many people that
I absolutely just love have
their lives ruined because

53:09.119 --> 53:10.454
of it.

